@node "Main" "VIO"
Variable Input/Output Routines

Included in this archive are routines that will allow you to use variables just as you would files.
Although string manipulation is fairly comprehensive in ARexx, it can be difficult to perform some
functions. After reading a moderately long file (up to 65535 characters) into a variable, these VIO
routines will allow you to:

  * Move a "pointer" forward or backwards through the variable-file
  * Read a series of line-feed-terminated lines from the variable-file,
    starting at the pointer location
  * Use string manipulation functions (eg, Insert(), DelStr(), and Translate())
    on the variable-file (not possible with a true file)

The function calls and arguments mirror the file manipulation functions:

  Open()    --> @{" OpenV()    " link "OpenV" 0}   : "Open" a variable for manipulation
  Close()   --> @{" CloseV()   " link "CloseV" 0}  : "Close" the variable
  Seek()    --> @{" SeekV()    " link "SeekV" 0}   : Reposition the variable's "pointer"
  ReadCh()  --> @{" ReadVCh()  " link "ReadVCh" 0} : Read the next character(s) from the variable
  ReadLn()  --> @{" ReadVLn()  " link "ReadVLn" 0} : Read the next LF-terminated line(s) from the variable
  WriteCh() --> @{" WriteVCh() " link "WriteVCh" 0} : Write the specified character(s) to the variable
  WriteLn() --> @{" WriteVLn() " link "WriteVLn" 0} : Write a LF-terminated line to the variable
  EOF()     --> @{" EOFV()     " link "EOFV" 0}    : Determine when the end of the variable is reached

  @{"Examples" link "Examples" 0}
  @{"History " link "History" 0}
@endnode

@node "OpenV" "OpenV()"
rv = OpenV(<variable>)
     rv is a Boolean value

Opens a variable with the name specified by <variable>, allowing it to be used by the other VIO
functions.

If the name of variable is to be entered directly, it must be in quotes:

    OpenSuccess = OpenV('ConfigFile')

The name of the variable may also be assigned to another variable, and that second, unquoted
variable used in the function:

    VarToOpen = 'ConfigFile'
    OpenSuccess = OpenV(VarToOpen)

Obviously this convention carries over to the other VIO functions as well

This function flags the variable as opened and initializes the variable pointer to 1.

  @{" Examples   " link "Examples" 0}

  @{" CloseV()   " link "CloseV" 0}
  @{" SeekV()    " link "SeekV" 0}
  @{" ReadVCh()  " link "ReadVCh" 0}
  @{" ReadVLn()  " link "ReadVLn" 0}
  @{" WriteVCh() " link "WriteVCh" 0}
  @{" WriteVLn() " link "WriteVLn" 0}
  @{" EOFV()     " link "EOFV" 0}
@endnode

@node "CloseV" "CloseV()"
rv = CLOSE(<variable>)
     rv is a Boolean value

Closes the specified <variable>. 0 will be returned if the variable had not been opened previously,
otherwise 1 will be returned.

<variable> is the case sensitive name of the variable of interest, the same variable used with the
OpenV() function.

This function flags the variable as closed, preventing any of the other VIO functions from being
used on the variable.

  @{" Examples   " link "Examples" 0}

  @{" OpenV()    " link "OpenV" 0}
  @{" SeekV()    " link "SeekV" 0}
  @{" ReadVCh()  " link "ReadVCh" 0}
  @{" ReadVLn()  " link "ReadVLn" 0}
  @{" WriteVCh() " link "WriteVCh" 0}
  @{" WriteVLn() " link "WriteVLn" 0}
  @{" EOFV()     " link "EOFV" 0}
@endnode

@node "SeekV" "SeekV()"
rv = SeekV(<variable>, <offset>, [<anchor>])
     rv is a number

Moves the pointer <offset> number of bytes from the <anchor> to a new position in the <variable>.
The <anchor> may be 'BEGIN', 'CURRENT', or 'END' (only the first character need be used). The
default <anchor> of 'C' will be used if nothing else is specified. <variable> must have been opened
previously with a call to OpenV().

The result is the new byte position relative to the beginning of the file.

If 'E' is the anchor, then <offset> should be a negative number to move the pointer backwards by
<offset> bytes.

Specifying SeekV('ConfigFile', 1) on the ConfigFile variable just opened will cause the pointer to
advance to the second character since the pointer initializes to the first character.

  @{" Examples   " link "Examples" 0}

  @{" OpenV()    " link "OpenV" 0}
  @{" CloseV()   " link "CloseV" 0}
  @{" ReadVCh()  " link "ReadVCh" 0}
  @{" ReadVLn()  " link "ReadVLn" 0}
  @{" WriteVCh() " link "WriteVCh" 0}
  @{" WriteVLn() " link "WriteVLn" 0}
  @{" EOFV()     " link "EOFV" 0}
@endnode

@node "ReadVCh" "ReadVCh()"
rv = ReadVCh(<variable>, [<length>])
     rv is the new string of read characters

Returns the number of characters specified by <length> (the default is 1) from <variable>, which
must have been opened with a prior call to OpenV().

The function will read a maximum of 65535 characters from the variable, but since the variable
could not have been more than 65535 characters long in the first place, this shouldn't present much
of a concern. Specifying a longer <length> will not cause an error, but also will not return more
than the 65535 characters.

This sets the pointer to the character after the last one read, or to the end of the variable if
<length> extends beyond the end of the variable

  @{" Examples   " link "Examples" 0}

  @{" OpenV()    " link "OpenV" 0}
  @{" CloseV()   " link "CloseV" 0}
  @{" SeekV()    " link "SeekV" 0}
  @{" ReadVLn()  " link "ReadVLn" 0}
  @{" WriteVCh() " link "WriteVCh" 0}
  @{" WriteVLn() " link "WriteVLn" 0}
  @{" EOFV()     " link "EOFV" 0}
@endnode

@node "ReadVLn" "ReadVLn()"
rv = ReadVLn(<variable>, [<count>], [<sepchar>])
     rv is a string

Returns the number of line-feed-terminated lines specified by <count> (the default is 1) from
<variable>, which must have been opened with a prior call to OpenV(). If <count> is greater than 1,
then the lines will be separated by <sepchar> (which defaults to the line-feed character, '0a'x).

This sets the pointer to the first character of the next line, or to the end of the variable if the
number of lines read extends beyond the end of the variable.

  @{" Examples   " link "Examples" 0}

  @{" OpenV()    " link "OpenV" 0}
  @{" CloseV()   " link "CloseV" 0}
  @{" SeekV()    " link "SeekV" 0}
  @{" ReadVCh()  " link "ReadVCh" 0}
  @{" WriteVCh() " link "WriteVCh" 0}
  @{" WriteVLn() " link "WriteVLn" 0}
  @{" EOFV()     " link "EOFV" 0}
@endnode

@node "WriteVCh" "WriteVCh()"
rv = WriteVCh(<variable>,<string>, [<option>])
     rv is a number

Writes the character(s) in <string> to <variable>, which must have been opened with a prior call to
OpenV().

The <option> may be 'BEGINNING', 'CURRENT', or 'END' (only the first character need be used) and
tells where <string> will be added. The <option> 'E' (the default) will cause the characters to be
appended to the end of the variable, 'B' will cause the original variable to be appended to the
characters, and 'C' will cause the characters to be inserted into the original variable before the
current position as indicated by the pointer.

This function will not append a newline character to <string>.

The return value from the function is a count of the characters written to the variable. If the
function was successful, the number returned will be equal to the length of <string>. A return of 0
indicates failure.

The pointer will be set to the character immediately after <string>.

  @{" Examples   " link "Examples" 0}

  @{" OpenV()    " link "OpenV" 0}
  @{" CloseV()   " link "CloseV" 0}
  @{" SeekV()    " link "SeekV" 0}
  @{" ReadVCh()  " link "ReadVCh" 0}
  @{" ReadVLn()  " link "ReadVLn" 0}
  @{" WriteVLn() " link "WriteVLn" 0}
  @{" EOFV()     " link "EOFV" 0}
@endnode

@node "WriteVLn" "WriteVLn()"
rv = WriteVLn(<variable>, <string>, [<option>])
     rv is a number

Writes <string> to <variable>, which must have been opened with a prior call to OpenV().

The <option> may be 'BEGINNING', 'CURRENT', or 'END' (only the first character need be used) and
tells where <string> will be added. The <option> 'E' (the default) will cause <string> to be
appended to the end of the variable, 'B' will cause the variable to be appended to <string>, and
'C' will cause <string> to be inserted into the variable before the current position as indicated
by the pointer.

This function appends a newline character to <string>.

The return value from the function is a count of the characters written to the variable. If the
function was successful, the number will be one more than the length of <string> since the function
counts the new-line character that it adds. A return of 0 indicates failure.

The pointer will be set to the character immediately after <string>.

  @{" Examples   " link "Examples" 0}

  @{" OpenV()    " link "OpenV" 0}
  @{" CloseV()   " link "CloseV" 0}
  @{" SeekV()    " link "SeekV" 0}
  @{" ReadVCh()  " link "ReadVCh" 0}
  @{" ReadVLn()  " link "ReadVLn" 0}
  @{" WriteVCh() " link "WriteVCh" 0}
  @{" EOFV()     " link "EOFV" 0}
@endnode

@node "EOFV" "EOFV()"
rv = EOFV(<variable>)
     rv is a Boolean value

The EOFV() function returns a Boolean flag of 1 (TRUE) when the end of the <variable> has been
reached; the result is FALSE (0) until the end of <variable> has been reached.

  @{" Examples   " link "Examples" 0}

  @{" OpenV()    " link "OpenV" 0}
  @{" CloseV()   " link "CloseV" 0}
  @{" SeekV()    " link "SeekV" 0}
  @{" ReadVCh()  " link "ReadVCh" 0}
  @{" ReadVLn()  " link "ReadVLn" 0}
  @{" WriteVCh() " link "WriteVCh" 0}
  @{" WriteVLn() " link "WriteVLn" 0}
@endnode

@node "Examples" "Examples"
 a = 'This is the original string.':

  1: say OpenV('a')
  2:   say SeekV('a', 8)
  3:   say WriteVCh('a', 'not ', 'C')
  4:   say a
  5:   say ReadVCh('a', 4)
  6:   say ReadVLn('a')
  7:   say SeekV('a', 0)
  8: say CloseV('a')

The results of the above code would be (note that the quotes are added for clarity only):
  1) 1 is returned (pointer is initialized to 1st character)
  2) 9 is returned (pointer is set to 9th character)
     An equivalent command would be SeekV('a', 9, 'B')
  3) 4 is returned (pointer is set to 13th character)
  4) 'This is not the original string.' is returned, no change to pointer)
  5) 'the ' is returned (pointer is set to 17th character)
  6) 'original string.' is returned (pointer is set to 33)
  7) 33 is returned (no change to pointer)
  8) 1 is returned (variable is closed)

==========================

Env:ConfigFile consists of:

  The
  quick
  brown
  fox
  jumps
  over
  the
  lazy
  doq.

Ignoring the leading spaces used only for this example, the character counts of each line are 4, 6,
6, 4, 6, 5, 4, 5, 5.

  1: call open('Temp', 'Env:ConfigFile')
  2: ConfigFile = ReadCh('Temp', 65535)
  3: call close('Temp')

  4: say OpenV('ConfigFile')
  5:   do i = 1 to 3
  6:     say ReadVLn('ConfigFile')
  7:   end
  8:   say ReadVLn('ConfigFile', 3)
  9:   say SeekV('ConfigFile', -10, 'E')
 10:   say ReadVLn('ConfigFile', 3)
 11: say CloseV('ConfigFile')

The results of the above code would be (note that the quotes are added for clarity only):
  1) The text file is opened
  2) The entire text file is read
  3) The text file is closed
  4) 1 is returned (pointer is initialized to 1st character) 5-7) 'The'
     'quick'
     'brown' is returned (the pointer is set to the beginning of 'fox')
  8) 'fox'
     'jumps'
     'over' is returned (the pointer is set to the beginning of 'the')
  9) 38 is returned (the pointer is set to the middle of the word 'lazy')
 10) 'zy'
     'dog.' is returned (the pointer is set beyond the end of the variable)
 11) 1 is returned (variable is closed)

  @{" OpenV()    " link "OpenV" 0}
  @{" CloseV()   " link "CloseV" 0}
  @{" SeekV()    " link "SeekV" 0}
  @{" ReadVCh()  " link "ReadVCh" 0}
  @{" ReadVLn()  " link "ReadVLn" 0}
  @{" WriteVCh() " link "WriteVCh" 0}
  @{" WriteVLn() " link "WriteVLn" 0}
  @{" EOFV()     " link "EOFV" 0}
@endnode

